    <div class="section">
      <h1>Teaching</h1>
      <p>I believe in inclusive, hands-on teaching that makes abstract concepts approachable and connected to real-world applications. I aim to foster curiosity and confidence in every student, whether in tutorials, labs, or one-on-one mentorship.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
      <h2>Teaching Assistant & Invigilator</h2>
      <p><strong>University of Toronto Mississauga (2025–present)</strong></p>
      <p>Supported undergraduate student learning by preparing and delivering tutorials, facilitating lab activities, and assisting with exam invigilation. Courses include:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>PSY344 — Forensic Psychology</li>
        <li>PSY393 — Human Neuropsychology</li>
        <li>PSY280 — Sensation & Perception</li>
        <li>PSY387 — Psychology of Music</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
      <h2>Mentorship</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Graduate Judge</strong>, STAR Program (2025) — Evaluated undergraduate research posters, providing constructive feedback on clarity, analysis, and presentation skills.</li>
        <li><strong>STEM Mentor</strong>, Letters to a Pre-Scientist (2024– ) — Long-term pen-pal mentorship with middle school students in underserved communities, encouraging representation and confidence in STEM pathways.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
      <h2>Teaching Philosophy</h2>
      <p>I strive to create learning environments where students feel both supported and challenged. My approach integrates active learning, collaborative discussion, and real-world connections, ensuring that students leave with both conceptual knowledge and practical skills.</p>
    </div>

